  "text": "Lower levels of thiol indicate more of an oxidized state in tobacco users. Tobacco consumption causes depletion of thiol (-SH groups) in the redox equation leading to a decrease in buffer activity of antioxidants, and thus tobacco use leads to cancer progression [CITATION_1] . Thus, for predicting the risk of oral carcinogenesis and overall survival of oral cancer patients, lipid peroxidation and thiol levels are useful biomarkers.",
